@node "About" "                         About IMTguide.rexx"

                        IMTguide.rexx v1.0  30-Oct-94
       Create Texture.guide from Imagine 3.0 texture.txt & litetex.txt
          Sample pics, Guide layout and Inspiration by Randy R. Wall
                          An ARexx hack by D.F. Duck

 IMTguide.rexx v1.0 reads Imagine 3.0 texture.txt & litetex.txt and writes
 Texture.guide, an AmigaGuide hypertext database. It will ask you several
 questions, where to put the guide file, where to put the sample pics, and
 what the path and filename of your picture viewer program is. You are
 given a chance to change any of these before proceding. From this infor-
 mation, the guide file that is written will be custom taylored to your
 system. We figured everyone already has their favorite pic viewer setup,
 so why should we force them to have another viewer program. The guide
 file will show the sample pics using the viewer program you already use.

                  @{" Requisites " link "Requisites"}   @{"    Use     " link "Use"}   @{"   Floppy   " link "Floppy"}
@endnode

@node "Requisites" "                 Requisites  -  Necessary Conditions"

 You must have ARexx installed and running. If you do not know how to do
 this then consult your local Amiga Guru or call Dirty Duck and ask.

 You must have the rexxsupport.library in your LIBS: assigned directory.
 This library comes with ARexx and os2.x so it -should- be already there.

 You must have your Imagine 3.0 distribution floppies DISK1: and DISK3:.
 OR - if you have the unaltered texture.txt (except the CTRL-M's removed)
 and litetex.txt files on your hard drive, copy them to RAM: before
 running IMTguide.rexx. If you do this IMTguide.rexx will not ask you to
 insert the floppy disks.

 A bit of drive space. The sample pics need about 500k, and the
 Texture.guide file and icon are just under 150k.

 You must have a hypertext reader in a PATH. AmigaGuide, MultiView, or
 AGuide will do the trick. The supplied icon for reading this database is
 setup to use AmigaGuide. If you use some other hypertext reader then edit
 the Texture.guide icon "ToolType".

@endnode

@node "Use" "                  Use  -  How do I run this thing?"

 Unarc the IMTguide.lha file to RAM: - if you don't have enough RAM: then
 you surely don't need this program because you couldn't run Imagine3
 anyway.


 To run from a Shell;

cd ram:
rx IMTguide.rexx


 To run from Workbench;

Double-click the IMTguide.rexx icon.
@endnode

@node "Floppy" "         Floppy  -  Putting Texture.guide on a floppy disk."

 The Texture.guide hypertext file, its icon, sample pics, and a viewer
 program WILL fit on a floppy disk.

 Format a blank floppy as IMTguide:

 Copy your favorite picture viewer program to this disk. When IMTguide.rexx
 asks you for the path to move the sample pics to enter IMTguide:pics and
 IMTguide.rexx will create the dir for you. When you are asked what your
 show program is enter IMTGuide:show (or whatever your view program name
 is). Do NOT enter DF0:show because then it will not work in any other
 drive. By specifying the volume name the Texture.guide file will be able
 to find the show program and pics no matter what floppy drive you put it
 into.

@endnode

@node "Randy" "              Randy R. Wall  -  Imagineer Extraordinare"

 I hope you find good use for this texture guide. It was developed from a
 texture guide I made for myself, and had hoped to distribute it over the 
 InterNET so many other Imagine users would be able to enjoy it as I do.
 But because of the copyright protection on the documentation by Impulse 
 I was unable to do so.

 Someone whom I don't remember mentioned that it would be neat to make an
 arexx script that could build the guide. Well sinse I'm not really an 
 arexx hacker I told him I doubt I could do it, but did know someone I
 thought could probably do it. That person was of course Dirty Duck.
 Being that the documentation was such a mess I knew this was asking a 
 lot of him. But as you will see he did an excellent job of converting 
 the docs into my Guide file. I personally would like to Thank him for the
 effort he put forth. Without his help this guide would not be possible.

 The guide has only the new 3.0 textures, we may add others. But for now 
 we just wanted to make the reading and finding of the many new textures 
 much easier. I had a heck of a time trying to get though the docs before
 as I would have to go into a text reader and then find the textures in
 the docs with a search command, and then scroll through the text. As you
 can imagine this was a real pain, and not very productive.
 
 Enter the world of Texture Guide, this Guide makes the process a snap. 
 You can either click buttons for the specific groups of textures or click
 the Texture List button for a complete display of all the textures. 
 I find this window very handy when you are working in Imagine and want 
 to be able to jump back and forth quickly from the guide and Imagine. 
 Its like having a quick reference of all the textures just a mouse click
 away. Well actually its not like having one, it is having one.

 I have included sample pictures with this guide as well. Many of them 
 are set at their defaults, but some I needed to tweak a bit. I tried to 
 stay as close to the defaults as possible. But the defaults did not 
 always achieve the sample pic I wanted to use, so I needed to modify
 some of them. They are only meant as samples to give you a rough idea of
 what the textures do. And are a far cry from showing you the texture at
 thier best settings. Duck also came up with the idea of having a Sample
 Picture Window. In this window you can get a quick look at any of the
 sample pictures. I didn't have this in my original Guide, but like it 
 very much. It is helpful when trying to quickly figure out what textures
 do what, without having to go through the text.
  
 Sinse this is our first attempt at this I thought I would wait and see
 what type of feedback we get before committing too much time getting the
 best pictures I can. I would like to know what formats would be most
 widely used and what sizes most of you would like. I was also trying to
 keep the size of the archive to a minimum. But if I find that many users
 want bigger and better pictures than I will probably make an updated 
 picture archive.

 One reason for this is I figured some of you with 24bit boards and AGA 
 systems may want to make up your own texture pics. I think it would really
 be nice if one had enough hard drive space to have full 24 bit versions 
 that could be displayed at the click of a button. Being that Duck made 
 the arexx script so when you build the guide you can set the show program
 to whatever you want, as well as place the pictures were you want, this 
 is completely possible. All you really need to do is replace my existing
 pics with yours, you will of course need to name them the same as the 
 ones I have supplied. You may also need to rebuild the guide and set the
 viewer to the viewer you use for your 24bit board, unless of course you
 do this the first time you have IMTguide build your guide file.

 Until you make your own, mine are here for your reference. They have
 been made to take up as little hard drive space as needed, so for those
 of you who value your hard drive space these samples should do the trick
 nicely.

 I hope you enjoy the guide, I tried to make it so its as user friendly 
 as possible, if you have comment or suggestions, or would just like to 
 say thanks. I can be reached at:

"Randy R. Wall" <rrw@ecst.csuchico.edu>

 Duck off and Fly BBS -  (916) 899-9811

 I would also like to mention that I'm sure Duck would like to hear your
 thanks, and comments as well, and if you would like this guide updated
 from time to time it would probably be a good idea to take the time and
 contact him at his BBS. Sinse he is asking nothing for this conversion
 script I don't think a call is too much for me to ask of you, even if it
 is long distance. If you use this guide as much as I do I'm sure it will
 be worth the price. He has thought of setting up a good 3D area, but needs
 to be sure it would be of use to his callers. So I'm sure if some of you
 start to make some calls he will do so. He also has most if not all of the
 newest archives on the InterNET, so I'm sure there will be something for
 you to find here as well. OK, yes this is my sales pitch for Ducks BBS as
 I am grateful for his help. But I would also like to see updates for this
 guide and know that if us Imagine folks don't let it be known that we 
 appreciate it, then this might just be the last Guide I will be able to
 distribute. So if you like it and use it, let it be known..If you don't
 like it, keep it to yourself and continue using the texture.txt file. Of
 course if you have suggestions we are always interested in hearing them.

 Duck can be reached at:

 Duck off and Fly BBS -  (916) 899-9811

 Well enough of me, go try this thing out and enjoy!

  =RRW=

@endnode

@node "Duck" "                      D.F. Duck  -  ARexx Hack"

 I have been playing with ARexx since early '87. I write games and utils
 for Skyline bbs and lots of shell scripts - some I release, most I just
 keep and use myself. I quite often write programs when someone asks me
 "can you do such'n'such in arexx?" - sometimes I can... I am NOT a
 programmer. I am just a simple hack and don't realy know what I'm doing,
 but do have a lot of fun.

 Randy was telling me about some Imagine3 users that had made a guide file
 from the texture.txt file. But they could not legaly distribute it to
 other users because of Impulses' copyright on the text - yada yada yada.
 He asked if I could write an ARexx program to convert the texture.txt
 file that comes on the Imagine3 distribution disk. I of course said
 "sure, no problem." Well, it did turn out to be a problem.. that text
 file is a MESS. I figure it must have been written by 8 differnt people
 ... on an IBM. The further I got into the project the more I realized
 just what I had gotten myself into. Besides the task of converting the
 text into hypertext, it also needed a lot of "cleaning up". The guide
 file that is created is not 100% cleaned up, but it is a lot easier on
 the eyes than the texture.txt file.

 The IMTguide.rexx code came out a little sloppy, but oh well. It could
 be faster and it could be smaller, but what the hey - you're only going
 to use it one time then toss it. Some of the slop was a result of an
 ARexx quirk - I discovered you can't call a procedure from a procedure
 and pass a variable as an arg. ARexx forgets what the variable definition
 is. Go figure. So I had to change  my procedures into subroutines and
 define a few more variables - that did the trick. At any rate, the
 program does what it is supposed to do, nothing more, nothing less.

 -IF- I get any response or feedback (not holding breath) on this project
 then I may write a follow-up program to read in the Texture.guide file,
 clean it up a bit more, and (optionaly) add the new Imagine3.1 textures.

    O<  Quack!                                     Duck
 *===
  ^
@endnode

